7h 00m

A one-day practical workshop to introduce and practice facilitation skills.

Goals / Learning Objectives

  • Develop/improve a shared understanding about what facilitation is and what the role of a facilitator is;
  • Give a basic toolkit for facilitating conversations and give opportunity for everyone to practice and receive feedback.
Beta
Time
Title and description
Additional Info
Materials

Room setup: Start in half-circle, and have a room (or set of rooms) that can accommodate small group work

09:00
10m

Welcome participants, do a check-in round.

Go through the high level agenda with timing and any housekeeping/logistics.

Give each trainer a moment to introduce themselves.

Introduce a Parking Lot poster in which to "park" any off topic questions.

This template is based on a real-life workshop the SessionLab team held at its 2025 team retreat: as such, it is tailored to a group of 12 people, who already know one another and work together. If you are working with larger groups or with people who do not know one another, adapt it by, for example:

  • adding getting-to-know you activities
  • having more parallel sessions and co-trainers, so everyone has the opportunity to practice
  • Flipchart with agenda
  • Parking lot flipchart
09:10
10m

Say a few words to frame the training. Why are we having this training? How can people benefit?

Alternative if having more time: ask people to note down on sticky notes for themselves, how can they benefit from improved facilitation skills and do a round of sharing (Increase duration for this activity appropriately)

It's useful to mention that participants may have more or less experience in facilitation already. If you are more experienced, consider giving more feedback and supporting others in their learning. If you are less experienced, welcome! We are here to learn and practice together.

    09:20
    5m

    This effective technique can be used at any meeting to make discussions more structured and efficient. By using simple hand gestures, participants can express different opinions and desires.


    Describe the various gestures and invite participants to use them throughout the training.

    Signs for requesting to speak/comment:

    • (1-finger): the participant wants to raise a new topic that is not a direct reply to the current discussion.
    • (2-fingers): the participant has a direct reply to the current topic/speaker.
    • (Pinky/little finger): there is a technical remark such as a factual mistake (e.g. we are looking at the wrong document) or other technical issues preventing the participants from properly following the meeting (e.g. participant cannot hear the person speaking).
    • (C-shape): the participant wants to request clarification on the topic or what the current speaker is saying.
    • (Cutting fingers): participants who had previously requested to speak but havent yet, can use this sign to signal to the facilitator that they are rescinding, or cutting, their request to speak.

    Signs for expressing opinion:

    • (3-fingers): the participant feels the discussion is off topic
    • (Thumbs up/horizontal/down): participants express support for, a neutral position or disagreement with an idea, argument, or proposal.
    • Flipchart with hand gestures
    09:25
    (25m)
    09:25
    10m

    Get on the same page about what the role of facilitator is. The purpose is not to align on one ultimate definition, but rather get people think of the roles & responsibilities and share views.



    Start with an empty flipchart, titled: "What does a Facilitator do?"

    And ask: Already in these first activities, and based on your previous experience, what would you say a facilitator does?


    Take note of the answers as they come in.

    • Flipchart paper
    • Markers
    09:35
    15m

    A creative drawing activity that helps participants build a shared vocabulary aroudn wah

    Many people have tried coming up with a metaphor for facilitation; what would yours be? Take a few minutes to draw it; give it a title if you like. Hang them up and take a walk about the gallery

    • Colours
    • A4 paper
    • Masking tape
    09:50
    5m

    Looking at the pictures and hanging them up is a natural space for a quick coffee break

      09:55
      5m

      During the rest of the training there will be various moments for giving and receiving feedback. Provide some pointers on how to do this in way that is effective and safe.

      • Remind people to take notes about their feedback during the activities so they know what to tell their peers;
      • Inform the group that you'll always be asking the people who were practicing to give their impressions first, before asking for other people's notes;
      • Provide a simple framework for giving feedback, such as Observation -> Feeling/need -> Advice for next time (or thank you!)


      • Flipchart prepared with feedback structure
      10:00
      (2h 50m)
      10:00
      5m

      Set up the ground for series of hands-on practice sessions


      Intro/Framing - 2 mins

      There are many aspects of what to pay attention as a facilitator. Today we're going to focus on some of the basic tools how to design and run effective meetings:

      • What tools you can use to facilitate conversations effectively
      • What tools you can use to move a process forward
      • How to design effective meetings/workshops


      Initial brainstorm - 3 mins

      Let's start with a quick brainstorming, what tools to are you already familiar with?

      Record input on sticky notes. Cluster them so there will be the following bigger groups:

      1. Simple verbal moderation tools (Probing, parahrasing, etc)
      2. Generic facilitation tools (Brainstorming, Clustering, Voting, etc.)
      3. More Specific workshop activities (OST, Word Caf, etc.)
      4. Misc?

      • Sticky notes
      • Markers
      • Flipchart
      10:05
      40m

      Practice simple moderation tools that are applicable when facilitating all types of conversations.




      Verbal facilitation tools (see attachment)


      1) Give 5 minutes for framing and setting up the groupwork


      We have 8 simple moderation tools. Create groups of 3/4 (2x4, 1x3) - we have three groups. Distribute the handouts to each group, and have it pre-marked, which tools (3, 3, 2) to they use)


      2) You have 5 minutes to review your tools, and come up with a way to demonstrate to the entire group, how to use them. That is, you will have an up to 3 minutes scene where you will use the tools on your list.


      3) After the 5 mins, coming back to full circle. Group one picks a topic and some (or all) members of the group facilitate a short conversation (we should provide a set of simple topics to choose from) and apply each technique. (3-4 mins per group)

      After each group's segment, we pause and:

      • ask the full group to identify which techniques were applied. When it is applied, note them on a flipchart.
      • encourage to give feedback on how these were applied

      Then the next group comes. So it's 3x5-6 mins (15-20 mins)


      4) Allow additional 10 minutes for sharing observations and tips/tricks about these tools (or buffer time).


      Tasks:

      Print and prepare handouts

      • Flipchart with title: Verbal Moderation Tools
      • Verbal Moderation Tools handout printed out + pre-marked for the group activities
      • Flipchart paper
      • Sticky notes
      • Markers
      10:45
      15m
        11:00
        5m

        Pick a quick energizer

          11:05
          1h 45m

          Get people practice simple facilitation tools to drive a meeting process forward. We pre-design the simple agendas, participants practice using the tools to open, diverge, converge.

          (Spare time by us designing the mini-agendas and which tools to use. It's focused only on practicing techniques)


          • Frame/brief the exercise (5 mins)
          • ask people to pick a tool (each tool printed on a single sheet of paper).
          • Reveal the short session designs, which sets the groups based on the tools people picked. You run the part that is to be run with your tool.
          • Give 10 mins for everyone to prepare for their segment (read your handout, and prepare how to run your part (use the first 5 minutes) Align with your co-facilitators, especially on how will you hand over to each other (what assets will the other do) - if needed, give 5 mins extra
          • Practice round (see the designs under Additional Info). 3x15 practice + 5 mins for feedback = 60 mins
          • Summary of tools used (5 mins)


          The key is designing approx 2 small agendas where the tools can be practiced.




          Tools to generate ideas:

          • Brainstorm (round robin vs popcorn)
          • Card survey
          • 1-2-4-All
          • Mind maps

          Tools to organise information:

          • Clustering
          • Parking lot

          Tools for evaluation

          • Flashlight
          • One-point survey
          • Dot voting / Multi-voting / Scoring methods
          • Quadrant diagrams

          Tasks:

          Prepare designs for mini-sessions (see examples below)

          Write designs up on flipcharts - 1 per team


          Designs

          1) Track 1 (You get a 5000 EUR budget to spend on employee happiness. Decide what do you do with it)

          • Brainstorm to generate ideas (4 mins)
          • Use Multi-voting to narrow down to the best idea(s) (5 mins) - feel free to adjust the voting system as you find best
          • Use a One-point Survey to query everyone's preference toward the most favoured option (2 mins)

          ===

          2) What type of non-financial actions would make us more happy and satisfied at SessionLab?

          • Open a Parking lot for ideas that don't relate to the core topic (2 mins)
          • Gather ideas with a Mind map (5 mins)
          • Run a Dot-voting to select best ideas (3 mins)
          • Run a Flashlight to understand current group sentiment (2 mins)

          ===

          3) Topic: How to celebrate successes in our company?

          • Run a Card Survey to gather ideas (3 mins)
          • Cluster ideas (4 mins)
          • Evaluate ideas in Quadrants (4 mins)
          • Run a One-Breath feedback to collect sentiment (2 mins)


          • Printouts of toolbox
          10m buffer before Lunch break
          13:00
          1h 15m
            14:15
            10m

            Pick an energizer that will help raise the energy after lunch and get everyone in a creative mood for the next activity.

              14:25
              (1h 15m)
              14:25
              5m

              Introducing the activity and presenting a simple framework for session design (Divergence / Emergence / Convergence)

              So far we've looked into how facilitation helps moderate conversations and how to lead activities. Now we will spend about an hour looking at where facilitators spend most of their time: planning and designing. You'll be paired up as co-facilitators and have 30 min to create an imaginary session that addresses a certain problem. We won't be actually holding those sessions, just looking at how the design process works. Let's remind ourselves of a few principles for good design of workshops:

              • the flow is important, usually from divergence to convergence
              • remember to include breaks and to make some provisions for keeping energy levels (can be energizers, but also varying type of activity helps)
              • try to include different activities, not just the ones that work for people who think just like you (e.g. activities for individuals, something with creativity...)
              • Divergence-emergence-convergence flipchart
              14:30
              40m

              Output: example session design that solves a problem/brief

              Paired work.


              • Randomized pairs
              • Each pair of "co-facilitators" gets three cards of three different colours:
                • session topic
                • session participants
                • other session information (duration, online/in person...)
              • This means you have a randomized brief for your session design; the stranger the combination, the better!
              • Feel free to make up any information you don't have: these are things your "client" has not decided yet so you can influence their decisions.


              Cards can be made based on the actual group's interests and needs. Some examples: Session topic:

                • 3 year vision
                • new product ideation
                • setting goals for a quarter
                • end-of-year team celebration

              Session participants:

                • your own team
                • the whole company
                • external stakeholders
                • the leadership team
                • a focus group of customers

              Other session information:

                • online
                • in person
                • lasting only 90 minutes
                • outdoors


              • Names of everyone in a "hat" for randomized pairing
              • Set of cards in three different colours for randomized briefs
              15:10
              30m

              Each pair presents their design and gets feedback from the group

              If time is running short, it is also possible to get two pairs of co-facilitators to present and critique to each other.

                15:40
                10m

                A moment to reflect and journal about next steps

                Write down one takeaway/tool that you want to use next time when you facilitate (or any other forward-looking commitment)

                  15:50
                  10m

                  How did the day go?

                  Ask for a round of feedback: how did the training go? What are people "taking home" from the experience?
